issue.title: Worker thread dies when AWS SDK throws and exeception
issue.body:

Fixed in 849d062179c5b0b631459bfc5fc477a8ff1e36e8

issue.title: Documention/Implementation of handling router errors
issue.body:
Hi, I am trying to user your router in a stand alone app (without the Hanami framework) and I am wondering if there is any documentation around how to handle errors before the request gets to a controller. For instance, how should I handle parsing errors?

Lets say I have this router implementation:
```ruby
$router = Hanami::Router.new(parsers: [:json]) do
  patch '/books', to: ->(env) { [200, {},[env['router.params'].inspect]] }
end
```

And in my config.ru I have something like this:

```ruby
map "/" do
  run $router
end
```

If I pass invalid JSON to /books, a Hanami::Routing::Parsing::BodyParsingError will be raised. But, if I want to handle that in a custom way, how would I implement that?

commits.message:
Merge pull request #1 from thomas07vt/catch-exceptions

Adding some exception handling code
Adding a method to calculate the time since last process.
Adding a rescue around each delete message block so we don't stop the whole delete process for 10 messages that fail.
Adding some to_i calls to make sure the options passed by users are correctly interpolated to integers.
Removing another old reference to queue that should be buffer.
I am dump and haven't been writing tests so I renamed a method and forgot to propgate the change accross the gem. I gotta have more cow... er tests

Adding a moving from calling the internal message queue, 'queue' to 'buffer' since we talk to the external sqs queue. Also adding a deep copy on the internal message buffer when we pass it to the outside world, so we don't have mutations.
Adding client class that should work. Need to write spec tests for this though.
